## 10. Styling & Theming

### Approach

* Centralized theme (colors, spacing, fonts)
* No inline magic numbers

```ts
theme.spacing.sm
theme.colors.primary
```

### Rules

* No hardcoded colors
* No duplicated spacing values
* Styles co-located with components

---

### 10.1 Dark Mode Support (MANDATORY)

> **Every UI component must support both light and dark themes.**

This is a non-negotiable requirement. A component that only looks correct in one theme is considered **incomplete**.

#### Required Pattern

All background, text, border, and icon colors must use NativeWind `dark:` variants:

```tsx
// ✅ Correct — theme-aware
<View className="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
  <Text className="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Hello</Text>
</View>

// ❌ Wrong — light mode only
<View className="bg-white">
  <Text className="text-gray-900">Hello</Text>
</View>
```

#### How Dark Mode Works in This Project

* Theme is controlled by `ThemeProvider` in `src/shared/contexts/ThemeContext.tsx`
* Uses `nativewindColorScheme.set()` for native and `document.documentElement.classList` for web
* Components do **not** need to read the theme directly — just use `dark:` class variants
* User preference is persisted via AsyncStorage

#### Checklist for Every New Component

- [ ] Background color has a `dark:` variant
- [ ] Text colors have `dark:` variants
- [ ] Border colors have `dark:` variants (if applicable)
- [ ] Icon colors respond to the current `colorScheme` (use `useTheme()` hook if needed)
- [ ] Component is visually verified in both light and dark mode

#### E2E Test Requirement

Per rule **20.1**, any component with theme-sensitive UI must have a Playwright test that:

* Verifies the component renders without errors after theme toggle
* Optionally verifies a background or text color class changes (if testable)

