## 11. Responsive & Cross-Device Behavior (WEB + MOBILE)

This section applies **equally to mobile and web builds**.
Nothing here is implicit — all frontend changes must be validated for **both mobile and web**.

---

### 11.1 Core Principle

> **Every frontend change must work correctly on both mobile and web.**

* Mobile and web share the **same codebase**
* Mobile is the **primary design target**
* Web is a **first-class supported platform**, not an afterthought

A change is considered **incomplete** if it:

* works only on mobile
* works only on web
* introduces layout or interaction regressions on either

---

#### 11.2 How This Is Achieved (Explicit, Not Implicit)

Responsive behavior is achieved primarily through **shared components and layout composition**, not platform forks.

We rely on:

* Flexbox (Yoga) layouts
* Responsive containers
* Shared components
* Conditional styling

---

### Clarification: Shared vs Platform-Specific Components

> **Platform-specific code is an exception, not the default.**

The following are considered **acceptable and non-contradictory**:

* `.native.tsx` / `.web.tsx` **only when UI primitives or platform capabilities differ**
* `Platform.OS` or `Platform.select()` **for small, localized differences**

The following are considered **forbidden forks**:

* Duplicating entire screens per platform
* Diverging business logic between platforms
* Maintaining separate navigation flows for web vs mobile

Rule of thumb:

* **Same feature, same behavior, same data flow**
* **Only rendering or interaction details may differ**

---

### 11.3 Supported Breakpoints

The application supports the following logical breakpoints:

* **Mobile:** width < 768px
* **Tablet:** 768px – 1024px
* **Desktop/Web:** > 1024px

Breakpoints are used to:

* adjust layout density
* change column count
* reposition secondary actions

Breakpoints must **never** change:

* business logic
* data fetching behavior
* feature availability

---

### 11.4 What Should Change Between Mobile and Web

| Aspect            | Mobile                      | Web                            |
| ----------------- | --------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| Layout            | Single column               | Multi-column where appropriate |
| Forms             | Full-width, stacked         | Centered, constrained width    |
| Primary actions   | Bottom-aligned or prominent | Inline with content            |
| Secondary actions | Hidden or collapsed         | Visible when space allows      |
| Navigation        | Stack / tabs                | Header or sidebar              |

---

### 11.5 What Must NOT Change Between Mobile and Web

The following must behave **identically**:

* Data shown
* Validation rules
* Error handling
* Loading states
* Navigation flow
* API interactions

If behavior differs between platforms, it is considered a **bug** unless explicitly approved.

---

### 11.6 Platform Detection Rules

Platform checks are allowed **only for layout or interaction differences**.

Allowed examples:

* Keyboard handling
* Hover effects on web
* Scroll behavior adjustments

Disallowed uses:

* Conditional business logic
* Conditional data fetching
* Feature enablement by platform

---

### 11.7 Developer Responsibility (IMPORTANT)

For every frontend change:

* Assume it will be used on **both mobile and web**
* Verify layout and interaction on:

  * at least one mobile form factor
  * at least one desktop/web form factor

If you cannot verify both:

* Stop
* Ask for confirmation before proceeding

---

❌ No duplicated screens per device
❌ No device-specific forks

